{
  "answer": "**The prayascittas (expiations or penances) for drinking surā (translated here as \"liquor,\" a distilled intoxicant) are not found in the short excerpt labeled as Manusmṛti chapter 11 in this corpus (verses 11.1–6, concerning gifts to Brahmins).**[^1]\n\n**They appear instead in the much longer section beginning at verse 11.7 (in the corpus's chapter 12), which continues the logical content of Manusmṛti chapter 11 on penances.**[^2] Specifically:\n\n- **11.90–92**: A twice-born (dvija) who drinks liquor out of delusion must either (i) drink boiling-hot liquor until death; (ii) drink heated cow's urine, milk, ghee, etc., until death; or (iii) for one year, eat grains or oil-cake only at night while dressed in haircloth with matted hair and carrying a banner.[^3]\n- **11.93–97**: Liquor (from molasses, grain, or honey) is equated with filth and sin; it is forbidden to Brahmins, Kshatriyas, and Vaishyas. Drinking it floods the Veda in one's body, reducing a Brahmin to Shudra status; it leads to delusion and forbidden acts.[^4]\n- **11.98**: These expiations conclude the topic before moving to theft.[^5]\n\n**Liquor drinking is one of the four \"great sins\" (mahāpātakas, alongside Brahmin-killing, gold theft, and defiling a guru's bed; see 11.54).**[^6]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 11](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/11/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 12](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/).\n\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [11.90–92](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-8246b0).\n\n[^4]: Manusmṛti, [11.93–97](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-d24880).\n\n[^5]: Manusmṛti, [11.98](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-54935a).\n\n[^6]: Manusmṛti, [11.54](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-961cc5).",
